## ✅ Week 2: Permissions, ACLs, and File Management

🎥 **Watch:**
- [Permissions Deep Dive (LearnLinuxTV)](https://youtu.be/6EibP2l_BmY)
- [ACLs Tutorial (Christian Lempa)](https://youtu.be/Nl3H_fN1gNc)

🛠 **Tasks:**
1. Create a directory `/project-data` owned by `brian`, group `developers`, permissions `2770`. 
[sudo mkdir /home/brian/project-data && sudo chown brian:developers /home/brian/project-data && sudo chown 2770 /home/brian/project-data] 
2. Set an ACL so that `sue` has read+write access to `/project-data` but not execute. 
[setfacl -m u:sue:rw /home/brian/project-data && sudo getfacl /home/brian/project-data]
3. Create a file `/tmp/testfile` and:
   - Set SUID and SGID [sudo chmod 6644 /tmp/testfile]
   - Make it read-only for everyone but `root` [sudo chmod 444 /tmp/testfile]
4. Find all files in `/etc` larger than 1MB:
[find /etc -type f -size +1M]
5. Use `rsync` to back up `/project-data` to `/backup/project-data`.
[sudo touch /home/brian/project-data/testfile.txt (to have a file to verify a transfer took place) && sudo mkdir /backup (to create the desination) && sudo rsync -rav /home/brian/project-data /backup/ && sudo ls /backup]

